<div data-component="page-shell" class="page">
  <header class="stagger">
    <p class="context-line">Steady / Health permissions</p>
    <div class="title-row">
      <h1>Replace startup-wide health permissions with feature-owned authorization without changing Steady&#39;s canonical data ownership</h1>
      <span class="status">ready for review</span>
    </div>
    <p class="dek">Move HealthKit authorization out of startup and into the feature that can explain each request, while SQLite remains canonical.</p>
  </header>

  <section id="outcome">
    <h2>What is meaningfully different</h2>
    <p>Health permissions now follow the feature that can explain why the data is needed. Steady no longer asks for every available HealthKit scope at launch: Initial Connect asks only for baseline readiness data, Workout Player asks for workout routes when route-aware playback opens, and Recovery asks for sleep stages when its trend screen opens.</p>
    <p>The trust boundary stays put. HealthKit supplies imported data; Steady's SQLite store remains the canonical source of truth. This changes when permission is requested, not where the product's data lives.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="before-after">
    <h2>Before and after: permission follows intent</h2>
    <div data-component="comparison-grid" class="comparison-grid">
      <div class="option-card">
        <h3>Before</h3>
        <p>App startup asked for every available HealthKit scope. A user could be prompted for data before opening the feature that needs it, including scopes unrelated to the first-run task.</p>
        <div class="best-for">startup request: 9 scopes</div>
      </div>
      <div class="option-card recommended">
        <h3>After</h3>
        <p><span class="recommend-mark">New mental model.</span> Each owning feature requests its scope at the moment the user enters the relevant flow, with Initial Connect limited to baseline readiness.</p>
        <div class="best-for">startup request: 3 baseline scopes</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>This is a narrower prompt surface without a second database or a change to the import boundary.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="ownership">
    <h2>Where each scope now belongs</h2>
    <div data-component="data-table" class="table-scroll table-stack">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Owning surface</th>
            <th>Scope</th>
            <th>Request moment</th>
            <th>Product consequence</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="cell-label" data-label="Owning surface">Initial Connect</td>
            <td data-label="Scope">Baseline readiness data</td>
            <td data-label="Request moment">Initial connection</td>
            <td data-label="Product consequence">Startup can establish readiness with 3 scopes instead of 9.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="cell-label" data-label="Owning surface">Workout Player</td>
            <td data-label="Scope">Workout routes</td>
            <td data-label="Request moment">Opening route-aware playback</td>
            <td data-label="Product consequence">Route access is explained in the playback flow that uses it.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="cell-label" data-label="Owning surface">Recovery</td>
            <td data-label="Scope">Sleep stages</td>
            <td data-label="Request moment">Opening the sleep trend screen</td>
            <td data-label="Product consequence">Sleep access is user-initiated and tied to a visible trend.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>No schema or migration changes are part of this change. SQLite remains Steady's canonical store for imported facts.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="review-path">
    <h2>Five-step review path</h2>
    <ol data-component="process-steps" class="process-steps">
      <li class="process-step">
        <span class="process-marker">1</span>
        <div class="process-title">Inspect ownership</div>
        <p class="process-detail">Confirm which feature can explain each HealthKit scope.</p>
      </li>
      <li class="process-step">
        <span class="process-marker">2</span>
        <div class="process-title">Route each scope</div>
        <p class="process-detail">Move requests from startup to the owning visible flow.</p>
      </li>
      <li class="process-step">
        <span class="process-marker">3</span>
        <div class="process-title">Preserve the store boundary</div>
        <p class="process-detail">Keep SQLite canonical; HealthKit stays an import source.</p>
      </li>
      <li class="process-step">
        <span class="process-marker">4</span>
        <div class="process-title">Run focused tests</div>
        <p class="process-detail">Check authorization behavior across the three owning features.</p>
      </li>
      <li class="process-step is-current">
        <span class="process-marker">5</span>
        <div class="process-title">Verify narrow UI states</div>
        <p class="process-detail">Use the simulator to confirm denial and recovery remain understandable.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section id="evidence">
    <h2>Evidence already in hand</h2>
    <div data-component="callout" class="callout">
      <p><strong>Confirmed.</strong> Fourteen authorization tests pass. The baseline startup request is reduced from 9 scopes to 3. There are no schema or migration changes, and route and sleep requests remain user-initiated.</p>
    </div>
    <p>These checks support the ownership and request-timing change. They do not by themselves prove that every denied-permission state is recoverable in the UI.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="risks">
    <h2>Risks to keep in view</h2>
    <p>Feature-owned authorization improves intent, but it moves responsibility to each feature. The current evidence covers three owning features; the remaining risk is behavioral recovery when a user declines access.</p>
    <div data-component="data-table" class="table-scroll table-stack">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Risk</th>
            <th>What could go wrong</th>
            <th>Current evidence</th>
            <th>Reviewer focus</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="cell-label" data-label="Risk">A feature forgets its scope</td>
            <td data-label="What could go wrong">A route or trend view opens without the data it needs.</td>
            <td data-label="Current evidence">Authorization tests cover Initial Connect, Workout Player, and Recovery.</td>
            <td data-label="Reviewer focus">Confirm each owning flow requests only on entry.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="cell-label" data-label="Risk">A denied scope is a dead end</td>
            <td data-label="What could go wrong">The user cannot understand or recover from declining sleep access.</td>
            <td data-label="Current evidence">Not yet verified in the simulator.</td>
            <td data-label="Reviewer focus">Check the denied-sleep recovery state before merge.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="cell-label" data-label="Risk">HealthKit becomes a second truth</td>
            <td data-label="What could go wrong">Imported data and app state drift into separate sources of truth.</td>
            <td data-label="Current evidence">SQLite remains canonical; no schema or migration changes.</td>
            <td data-label="Reviewer focus">Keep the import boundary intact.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section id="decision">
    <h2>Decision and remaining check</h2>
    <div data-component="callout" class="callout warn">
      <p><strong>Remaining check.</strong> The denied-sleep recovery state is the one simulator check still outstanding. Confirm that the Recovery trend screen explains the denial and offers a recoverable path.</p>
    </div>
    <div data-component="recommendation" class="recommendation">
      <p><strong>Approve after confirming the denied-sleep recovery state in the simulator.</strong> The requested scopes are now owned by the feature that uses them, startup prompts are narrower, and Steady's canonical SQLite boundary is unchanged.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <footer class="sources">Source: supplied change facts for this review walkthrough.</footer>
</div>

